    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3071230669" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3071230669" />
    <a title="Howard" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/32041201-howard"><img alt="Howard" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1587918150p2/32041201.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3071230669?book_show_action=true">Dec 03, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Howard" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Howard" href="/user/show/32041201-howard">Howard</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780156364652" href="/book/show/432341.A_Good_Man_Is_Hard_to_Find_and_Other_Stories">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/32041201-howard?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/32041201-howard?shelf=american-south">american-south</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/32041201-howard?shelf=reviewed">reviewed</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/32041201-howard?shelf=short-stories">short-stories</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3071230669" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7419657349880316942"><b>SARDONIC</b><br/>Sardonic is an adjective resorted to by many a critic in their efforts to explain Flannery O’Connor and her writing. According to Merriam-Webster the word can be defined as “disdainfully or skeptically humorous; derisively mocking.” It is a perfect description of the writer and her work.<br/><br/>Here is an example of O’Connor’s sardonic humor:<br/><br/><i>Everywhere I go, I’m asked if the universities stifle writers. My opinion is that they don’t stifle enough of them. There’s many a best seller that could ha</i></span>
  <span id="freeText7419657349880316942" style="display:none"><b>SARDONIC</b><br />Sardonic is an adjective resorted to by many a critic in their efforts to explain Flannery O’Connor and her writing. According to Merriam-Webster the word can be defined as “disdainfully or skeptically humorous; derisively mocking.” It is a perfect description of the writer and her work.<br /><br />Here is an example of O’Connor’s sardonic humor:<br /><br /><i>Everywhere I go, I’m asked if the universities stifle writers. My opinion is that they don’t stifle enough of them. There’s many a best seller that could have been prevented by a good teacher.</i><br /><br />One of the stories in the <i>A Good Man is Hard to Find and Other Stories</i> collection is <i>The Life You Save May Be Your Own</i>. She sold the film rights to the story, thereby waiving any chance to influence what might eventually appear on the screen. In 1957, it was produced as an episode on a TV anthology series known as the “Schlitz Playhouse of Stars.” <br /> <br />For some reason, the character Tom T. Shiflet’s name was changed to Tom T. Triplet. I point that out only because Shiftlet – as in shifty or shiftless – was a name chosen by O’Connor as shorthand for a character who cons a widow, marries and deserts her deaf mute daughter, and drives off in the widow's car.<br /><br />Maybe the reason that the film’s producers changed the name is because Gene Kelly was cast in the role. Yes, that Gene Kelly, the wholesome, exuberant, singin’ and dancin’ in the rain, Gene Kelly, was chosen to portray the amoral drifting grifter. So, maybe not only the name of the character was changed; perhaps he was given some redeeming qualities; or he and the deaf mute daughter lived happily ever after. I don’t know for I have never watched the episode nor know of anyone who has even heard of it.<br /><br />O’Connor’s reaction:<br /><br />“A story I sold will star a tap dancer….The punishment always fits the crime.”<br /><br />O'Connor was confident that her story would be butchered beyond recognition. She wrote that “Mr. Shiftlet and the idiot daughter will no doubt go off in a Chrysler and live happily ever after. Anyway…while they make hash out of my story, Regina (her mother) and me will make ice in the new refrigerator.”<br /><br />The refrigerator was purchased with the money she received for the film rights to the story. So it wasn’t a total loss.<br /><br /><br /><b>“I don’t deserve any credit for turning the other cheek as my tongue is always in it.” – Flannery O’Connor</b><br /><br /><br /><b>GROTESQUE</b><br /><b>“Anything that comes out of the South is going to be called grotesque by the northern reader, unless it is grotesque, in which case it is going to be realistic.” – Flannery O’Connor</b><br /><br />Grotesque, defined as fanciful, bizarre; absurdly incongruous; departing markedly from the natural, the expected, or the typical, is another adjective used by critics in their descriptions of O’Connor’s stories.<br /><br />One would have to agree that they most assuredly depart from the natural or the expected or the typical, and that they are sometimes fanciful or bizarre or incongruous, and, yes, absurdly so, and in some stories all of the above is true.<br /><br />How else could one characterize a story in which a criminal murders a family that is on vacation or a Bible salesman who seduces a lonely college-educated woman and then steals her artificial leg? Those are two of the stories included in <i>A Good Man is Hard to Find and Other Stories.</i><br /><br />O’Connor described the collection as “nine stories about original sin with my compliments.” A number of the characters are “small-minded, ignorant, vain, parochial and smug widows,” self-righteous people who are quick to criticize and denounce the shortcomings that they see in others, but are blind to their own, but in the end always receive their comeuppance. (Some critics speculate that their model was her widowed mother, who confessed that she didn’t like or understand the stories that her daughter wrote.)<br /><br />Something bad is bound to happen in her stories, but even that awareness does not prepare the reader for the fate of the widowed grandmother in the title story. The climax is so shocking that Rod Serling would not have touched that story with a ten foot pole.<br /><br /><b>“I come from a family where the only emotion respectable to show is irritation. In some this tendency produces hives, in others literature, in me both.” – Flannery O’Connor</b><br /><br />Finally a bit of trivia:<br /><br />1) Did you know that Tommy Lee Jones wrote his thesis at Harvard on Flannery O’Connor?<br /><br />2) Did you know Tommy Lee Jones was a Harvard alumnus?<br /><br />3) Bonus: Who was Jones’ Harvard roommate?</span>
  <a data-text-id="7419657349880316942" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


