  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1750042466" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1750042466" />
    <a title="Paul Haspel" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/40256937-paul-haspel"><img alt="Paul Haspel" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1425160128p2/40256937.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1750042466?book_show_action=true">Sep 06, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Paul Haspel" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Paul Haspel" href="/user/show/40256937-paul-haspel">Paul Haspel</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback " href="/book/show/11367079-a-good-man-is-hard-to-find-and-other-stories">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/40256937-paul-haspel?shelf=southern-lit">southern-lit</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1750042466" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17399456867102674500">A good story is *not* hard to find in this classic collection by one of the greatest Southern U.S. writers. Working at the height of her powers, Flannery O’Connor sets down, in an unforgettable manner, her unique and distinctive sense of the life of her region, in the ten stories that make up her 1955 collection <i>A Good Man Is Hard to Find and Other Stories</i>.<br/><br/>Flannery O’Connor is nowadays so taken-for-granted as one of the pre-eminent writers of the Southern Literary Renaissance that it is easy to </span>
  <span id="freeText17399456867102674500" style="display:none">A good story is *not* hard to find in this classic collection by one of the greatest Southern U.S. writers. Working at the height of her powers, Flannery O’Connor sets down, in an unforgettable manner, her unique and distinctive sense of the life of her region, in the ten stories that make up her 1955 collection <i>A Good Man Is Hard to Find and Other Stories</i>.<br /><br />Flannery O’Connor is nowadays so taken-for-granted as one of the pre-eminent writers of the Southern Literary Renaissance that it is easy to forget the ways in which she broke with the prevailing values and mores of the American South. She was a woman in a male-dominated region. She was a devout Roman Catholic in a part of the United States where evangelical Protestantism dominated everyday life and dictated social codes. <br /><br />And, diagnosed at age 27 with the systemic lupus erythematosus that took her life 12 years later, she knew what it was to be a person with a disability in a region that looked at “different-ness” of any kind with distrust, or worse. All of these factors from her life no doubt contributed to the way in which she created characters who are often “misfits” of one kind or another – characters who often end up in situations that are violent and/or horrifying, and who yet have the potential to experience some sort of moment of grace.<br /><br />The title story, “A Good Man Is Hard to Find,” is one of those stories that is often described as “heavily anthologized” – meaning, in other words, that you would have to look hard to find a college-level literature anthology that does not contain this story. Yet the reason why it is so heavily anthologized is that it is, purely and simply, a great story, and one that is strongly characteristic of O’Connor’s literary sensibility and thematic concerns.<br /><br />The story also shows the ways in which O’Connor’s South is different from that of, say, William Faulkner. O’Connor’s is an urbanizing and suburbanizing South, as shown in this story of an Atlanta-area family who, en route to their planned Florida vacation, have to drive a long way just to get out of the city (an experience with which many I-285/Perimeter drivers of today could no doubt identify). <br /><br />The story’s protagonist, the grandmother of the family, is an embodiment of various Southern prejudices – always ready with a racist joke against African Americans, and obsessed with her status as a “lady” of presumably higher-than-someone-else social station. And the story’s title comes from a moment when the family stops at a barbecue restaurant and the restaurant’s proprietor, one “Red Sammy,” says, “A good man is hard to find….Everything is getting terrible. I remember the day you could go off and leave your screen door unlatched. Not no more” (p. 16). Red Sammy’s nostalgic idealization of the past captures the falsity of thinking that characterizes the grandmother, and so many of O’Connor’s characters.<br /><br />But the grandmother’s race and class prejudices do not protect her when some bad decisions on her part cause the family to have a deadly run-in with an escaped convict known as “the Misfit,” who laments that he did not live in Biblical times and therefore was not there to see whether or not Jesus of Nazareth could truly raise the dead. Only when she is on the verge of losing everything she holds dear does the grandmother, nominally a devout Protestant, truly realize her kinship with all of fallen humankind, as she reaches out toward the murderous Misfit and says, “Why, you’re one of my babies. You’re one of my own children!” (p. 29)<br /><br />Another canonical O’Connor story from this collection is one whose title I am going to refer to simply as “The Artificial” – because the n-word (yes, <i>the</i> n-word) is part of the title. “The Artificial” shares the Atlanta setting of the story "A Good Man Is Hard to Find"; and like that title story of this collection, "The Artificial" also presents a thoroughly unpleasant grandparent as protagonist - one Mr. Head, who is taking his grandson Nelson on a train trip into the city. Each constantly tries to pull rank on the other – Nelson because he has visited Atlanta before (though only as a very small child), and Mr. Head because, unlike Nelson, he has seen African Americans (the last African-American resident of Mr. Head’s county was driven out 12 years prior). <br /><br />The trip goes drastically wrong, and Mr. Head shows himself capable of a terrible act of abandonment against Nelson; but just when it seems as though this trip to the big city can only end in disaster, the two encounter, in an affluent suburban area of Atlanta, a racist lawn-ornament statue of an African American – an “artificial Negro.” After all that they have been through, and all of the hostility that they have expressed toward each other, Mr. Head and Nelson “stood gazing at the artificial Negro as if they were faced with some great mystery, some monument to another’s victory that brought them together in their common defeat. They could both feel it dissolving their differences like an action of mercy” (p. 128).<br /><br />“Good Country People,” another of the more canonical stories in this volume, takes its title from the declaration by Mrs. Hopewell, the owner of a Georgia farm, that the Freemans, a couple she has hired to help her run the farm, “were not trash. They were good country people” (p. 170) - another instance of O'Connor revealing the deep-seated class prejudices of the South. But the true focus of the story is Mrs. Hopewell’s daughter Joy, who has renamed herself “Hulga” because it is the ugliest name she can think of. <br /><br />Joy/Hulga, in response to her mother’s relentless cheerfulness, has recast herself as a sort of philosophical nihilist; she is an avid reader of Heidegger (interesting choice, that, as Heidegger was a supporter of Nazism before, during, and even after the Second World War), and she may remind you of that student you knew in your sophomore year at college who thought it was oh-so-cool to believe in nothing. Yet Joy/Hulga gets her comeuppance at the hands of a traveling Bible salesman named Manley Pointer (great name), who, once he has gotten the better of Joy/Hulga, dismisses Joy/Hulga’s fashionable nihilism with a devastating rejoinder: “[Y]ou ain’t so smart. I been believing in nothing ever since I was born!” (p. 195)<br /><br />The other stories may not be as well known, outside the realm of Southern literature, but each one has its own special power. “The River,” the story of a boy who takes Biblical accounts of total-immersion baptism quite literally, generates almost unbearable suspense as the main character walks into a river to self-baptize: “He only saw the river, shimmering reddish yellow, and bounded into it with his shoes and his coat on and took a gulp. He swallowed some and spit the rest out and then he stood there in water up to his chest and looked around him….He intended not to fool with preachers any more but to Baptize himself, and to keep on going this time until he found the Kingdom of Christ in the river” (p. 51).<br /><br /> “A Late Encounter with the Enemy,” the story of a superannuated Confederate veteran who has become an object of celebration by a Civil War-nostalgic Southern culture, is of interest chiefly for its scrutiny of the way in which many Americans from both North and South, during the time around the Civil War Centennial of 1961-65, wanted to celebrate the heroism of Civil War soldiers without addressing the issues over which the Civil War was fought. Yet the “General Sash” who is the main character of the story turns out not to be a general at all; “He had not actually been a general in that war. He had probably been a foot soldier; he didn’t remember what he had been; in fact, he didn’t remember that war at all” (p. 157).<br /><br />And “The Displaced Person,” the story that concludes this collection, may be best understood in terms of the post-World War II milieu within which O’Connor was composing. “Displaced person” may not be such a familiar term nowadays, but the term “displaced persons’ camp” would have been quite familiar to people who knew of many such camps being established for Holocaust survivors after the end of the Second World War. In the case of this story, the title character, a Pole and a Holocaust survivor, comes to post-World War II Georgia and, through his hard work and his knowledge of agricultural life, distinguishes himself as a foreman on a Georgia farm; but when his egalitarian ways bring him to question the South’s unjust racial norms, the stage is set for tragedy.<br /><br />I re-read <i>A Good Man Is Hard to Find and Other Stories</i> in the context of two trips to Georgia earlier this year. In towns like Brunswick and Hinesville and Midway, I could imagine characters from O'Connor's stories coming to life before me -- Bailey scowling behind the wheel of his car at a stoplight, while the grandmother from the collection's title story tells him that his travel directions are all wrong; Nelson and Mr. Head arguing on the sidewalk in front of a hardware store; Joy/Hulga complaining that the town library contains no books by Heidegger; General Sash's descendants at the county courthouse, protesting plans to take down a Confederate-soldier monument. O'Connor's stories, for all their elements that may seem odd or distorted, are that vivid in terms of the fictive world that they create. <br /><br />This short-story collection covers a lot of ground in a mere 251 pages. One need not share O’Connor’s religious beliefs to be moved and impressed by the way in which O’Connor sets forth her insights regarding the human search for meaning and truth in life.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17399456867102674500" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

